high_profile_info.FullDescription:
[SQLite](https://www.sqlite.org/) is a software library that provides a lightweight, self-contained, serverless, and transactional SQL database engine. It is widely used as an embedded database in various applications and devices due to its simplicity, reliability, and small footprint.
[SQLite OS Interface or VFS (Virtual File System)](https://www.sqlite.org/vfs.html) is a component of SQLite that allows developers to customize the way SQLite interacts with the underlying file system. 
The primary purpose of the VFS is to handle low-level file operations such as opening, reading, writing, and closing database files.

When using the [appendvfs](http://www.sqlite.org/src/file/ext/misc/appendvfs.c) API to open an appended file, SQLite expects to find a database in the provided file, usually at the end of the appended file.
However, if there is no SQLite database file in the appended file, the `apndOpen()` function of the `appendvfs` code tries to close an empty handle, causing an out-of-bounds read which leads to a denial of service.
By default, the sqlite library does not use the vulnerable `appendvfs` function. To use it, the extension `appendvfs` should be registered in the VFS list through either `sqlite3_appendvfs_init()` or `sqlite3_vfs_register()` functions.

The published [PoC](https://github.com/Tsiming/Vulnerabilities/blob/main/SQLite/CVE-2021-31239) leads to denial of service. 
This issue can be triggered when opening the file with sqlite3 through the command line: `sqlite3 < poc`.

Example of vulnerable code:
```
int main (void)
{
    sqlite3_appendvfs_init(0, 0, 0);
    int flags = SQLITE_OPEN_READWRITE|SQLITE_OPEN_CREATE;
    sqlite3 *db;
    if (sqlite3_open_v2("poc", &db, flags, "apndvfs") != SQLITE_OK) {
        printf("%s\n", sqlite3_errmsg(db));
    } else {
       // in case it succeeds to open the file
    }
    sqlite3_close(db);
    exit(0);
}
```
The `sqlite3_appendvfs_init()` function is registering the `appendvfs` extension to sqlite3.

